					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Tie=
breaker used to rank sport teams on equal points in a league competition</d=
iv>
<p><b>Goal difference</b>, <b>goal differential</b> or <b>points difference=
</b> is a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiebreaker" titl=
e=3D"Tiebreaker">tiebreaker</a> used to rank sport teams which finish on eq=
ual points in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sports_league" tit=
le=3D"Sports league">league competition</a>. Either "goal difference" or "p=
oints difference" is used, depending on whether matches are scored by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goal_(sport)" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Goal (sport)">goals</a> (as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ice_hockey" title=3D"Ice hockey">ice hockey</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_football" title=3D"Association football">a=
ssociation football</a>) or by points (as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rugby_union" title=3D"Rugby union">rugby union</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basketball" title=3D"Basketball">basketba=
ll</a>).
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:The_North_End_Football_Club_(1885-03-07).png"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/The_North_End_Football_Club_%281885-03-07%29.png/=
250px-The_North_End_Football_Club_%281885-03-07%29.png" decoding=3D"async" =
width=3D"250" height=3D"351" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1=
098" data-file-height=3D"1542"></a><figcaption>Early example of goal averag=
e being used to compare the performances of football clubs (March 1885)</fi=
gcaption></figure>
<p>Goal difference is calculated as the number of goals scored in all leagu=
e matches minus the number of goals conceded, and is sometimes known simply=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plus%E2%80%93minus_(sports)" t=
itle=3D"Plus=E2=80=93minus (sports)">plus=E2=80=93minus</a>. Goal differenc=
e was first introduced as a tiebreaker in association football, at the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1970_FIFA_World_Cup" title=3D"1970 FIF=
A World Cup">1970 FIFA World Cup</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mathletics_1-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goal_difference#=
cite_note-Mathletics-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and was adopted by the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Football_League" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"F=
ootball League">Football League</a> in England five years later.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Mathletics_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Goal_difference#cite_note-Mathletics-1"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It has since =
spread to many other competitions, where it is typically used as either the=
 first or, after tying teams' head-to-head records, second tiebreaker.=20
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Average"></span>Goal difference has oft=
en replaced the older <b>goal average</b>, or <b>goal ratio</b>. Goal avera=
ge is the number of goals scored divided by the number of goals conceded,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Goal_difference#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and is therefore a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionless_quantity" title=3D"Dimensio=
nless quantity">dimensionless quantity</a>. It was replaced by goal differe=
nce, which was thought to encourage more attacking play, encouraging teams =
to score more goals (or points) as opposed to defending against conceding.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mathletics_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goal_difference#cite_note-Mathletics-1"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> How=
ever goal average is still used as a tiebreaker in Australia, where it is r=
eferred to as "<b>percentage</b>". This is calculated as points scored divi=
ded by points conceded, and then multiplied by 100.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goal_difference=
#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If two or more teams' total points scored and goal differences are b=
oth equal, then often goals scored is used as a further tiebreaker, with th=
e team scoring the most goals winning.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goal_difference#cite_note-4"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> After this a variety of other tiebreakers may be used.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Goal_difference_v._goal_ave=
rage">Goal difference <i>v.</i> goal average</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGoal_difference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Goal difference v. goal average"><span>edit=
